# EPF Framework Content Definition
# 
# This file explicitly defines what counts as "framework content" for versioning.
# Any changes to files matching these patterns require a version bump.
#
# Used by: scripts/classify-changes.sh
# Last updated: 2026-01-03

# ============================================================================
# FRAMEWORK CONTENT (Changes require version bump)
# ============================================================================

# Core schemas (validation rules)
schemas/*.json
schemas/_legacy/*.json

# Templates (READY/FIRE/AIM artifacts)
templates/**/*.yaml
templates/**/*.md

# Documentation (framework guides)
docs/*.md
docs/guides/*.md
docs/guides/technical/*.md
README.md
MAINTENANCE.md
CANONICAL_PURITY_RULES.md

# Wizards (AI-assisted content creation)
wizards/*.md

# Scripts (automation, validation, hooks)
scripts/*.sh
scripts/hooks/*.sh

# Output generators (external artifact generation)
outputs/**/*.json
outputs/**/*.md
outputs/**/*.sh
outputs/**/*.yaml

# Feature corpus (validated feature definitions)
features/**/*.yaml
features/**/*.md

# Integration specification
integration_specification.yaml

# Version tracking
VERSION

# Instance structure documentation (but NOT instances themselves)
_instances/README.md

# ============================================================================
# NON-FRAMEWORK CONTENT (Changes do NOT require version bump)
# ============================================================================
# These are explicitly excluded from version bump requirements:
#
# .epf-work/               - Temporary working files, session notes
# .github/                 - CI/CD config, GitHub infrastructure
# _instances/*/**          - Instance examples (except README.md)
# _legacy/**               - Deprecated/archived content (except schemas/_legacy/)
# .gitignore, .git/        - Git configuration
# node_modules/, venv/     - Dependencies (should not be committed)

# ============================================================================
# ADDING NEW FRAMEWORK CONTENT
# ============================================================================
#
# When adding a NEW directory that is framework content:
#
# 1. Add pattern to this file under "FRAMEWORK CONTENT"
# 2. Update scripts/classify-changes.sh:
#    - Add counter variable (e.g., NEW_DIR_CHANGED=0)
#    - Add case pattern in classification loop
#    - Add display line in summary
#    - Add logic to set NEEDS_VERSION_BUMP and RECOMMENDED_TYPE
# 3. Determine default bump type:
#    - MAJOR: Breaking changes to existing functionality
#    - MINOR: New features, additive changes
#    - PATCH: Fixes, documentation improvements
# 4. Test with: ./scripts/classify-changes.sh
# 5. Update this file's "Last updated" date
# 6. Commit changes to classifier
#
# Example workflow:
#   # You create new directory: modules/
#   echo "modules/**/*.ts" >> .epf-framework-content
#   # Update classify-changes.sh (add MODULES_CHANGED counter, case, logic)
#   ./scripts/classify-changes.sh  # Test it works
#   git add .epf-framework-content scripts/classify-changes.sh
#   git commit -m "feat(scripts): Add modules/ as framework content"
#
# ============================================================================

# Future-proofing notes:
# - If unsure whether something is framework content, err on the side of YES
# - Unclassified files trigger warnings in classify-changes.sh
# - Review this file when restructuring EPF
# - Keep patterns specific (use **/ for recursive, * for single level)
